            <section class="prose mt-10">
              <h2>What is loan prepayment?</h2>
              <p>
                Loan prepayment means paying back part or all of your loan
                earlier than the agreed schedule. Instead of only making the
                minimum required payment, you can:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Add extra to each regular payment</strong> (e.g. +$100
                  per month).
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Make one or more lump-sum payments</strong> (e.g.
                  using a bonus or inheritance).
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Pay off the entire balance early</strong> (full
                  prepayment).
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                For standard amortizing loans (mortgages, personal loans, auto
                loans), interest is calculated on the outstanding principal.
                Reducing the principal faster through prepayment usually cuts
                both the total interest paid and the time it takes to become
                debt-free.
              </p>

              <h2>How this loan prepayment calculator works</h2>
              <p>This calculator builds two amortization schedules:</p>
              <ol>
                <li>
                  <strong>Original schedule</strong> – based on your loan
                  amount, interest rate, term, and payment frequency.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Prepayment schedule</strong> – applies your chosen
                  extra payments and lump sums, plus any prepayment penalty.
                </li>
              </ol>

              <h3>1. Monthly (or periodic) payment formula</h3>
              <p>
                For a fixed-rate amortizing loan, the regular payment \(PMT\)
                is:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>Let:</p>
                <ul>
                  <li>\(P\) = principal (loan amount)</li>
                  <li>
                    \(r\) = periodic interest rate (annual rate / payments per
                    year)
                  </li>
                  <li>
                    \(n\) = total number of payments (years × payments per year)
                  </li>
                </ul>
                <p>Then the payment is:</p>
                <p>\[ PMT = P \cdot \frac{r(1+r)^n}{(1+r)^n - 1} \]</p>
              </div>

              <h3>2. Amortization step-by-step</h3>
              <p>For each payment period \(k\):</p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>
                  \[ \text{Interest}_k = \text{Balance}_{k-1} \cdot r \] \[
                  \text{Principal}_k = PMT - \text{Interest}_k \] \[
                  \text{Balance}_k = \text{Balance}_{k-1} - \text{Principal}_k -
                  \text{Extra}_k - \text{Lump}_k \]
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>
                The calculator repeats this until the balance reaches zero. When
                prepayments are applied, the balance drops faster, so fewer
                periods are needed.
              </p>

              <h3>3. Prepayment penalties</h3>
              <p>
                Some lenders charge a <strong>prepayment penalty</strong> if you
                repay early. Common structures include:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Percentage of remaining balance</strong> – e.g. 2% of
                  the outstanding principal.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Months of interest</strong> – e.g. 3 months of
                  interest on the current balance.
                </li>
                <li><strong>Flat fee</strong> – a fixed dollar amount.</li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                In this tool, the penalty (if any) is applied once when your
                first prepayment occurs within the penalty period you specify.
                The penalty is added to the total cost in the prepayment
                scenario so you can see the
                <strong>net interest savings</strong>.
              </p>

              <h2>How to interpret the results</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Total interest (original vs. prepayment)</strong> –
                  shows how much interest you avoid by paying early.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Number of payments</strong> – indicates how many
                  months or weeks you shave off the term.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Interest saved</strong> – includes the effect of any
                  prepayment penalty.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Time saved</strong> – converted into years and months
                  for easier understanding.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>Example: Small extra payment, big impact</h3>
              <p>
                Suppose you have a $250,000 mortgage at 6% for 30 years, paid
                monthly:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>Regular payment ≈ $1,499.</li>
                <li>Total interest over 30 years ≈ $289,595.</li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                If you add just <strong>$200 extra per month</strong> from the
                start:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>You pay off the loan several years earlier.</li>
                <li>You save tens of thousands of dollars in interest.</li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                The exact numbers depend on your rate and timing, which this
                calculator computes for you.
              </p>

              <h2>Pros and cons of loan prepayment</h2>
              <h3>Advantages</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>Lower total interest cost.</li>
                <li>Shorter time in debt and improved peace of mind.</li>
                <li>Higher equity in your home or asset.</li>
                <li>
                  Better resilience to income shocks once the loan is gone.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>Potential drawbacks</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>Prepayment penalties can reduce or offset the benefit.</li>
                <li>
                  Less liquidity: money tied up in the loan is harder to access.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Opportunity cost: you might earn more by investing instead of
                  prepaying.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Tax considerations: in some countries, mortgage interest is
                  tax-deductible.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Frequently asked questions</h2>

              <h3>1. Does prepaying always reduce my monthly payment?</h3>
              <p>
                Not necessarily. Many lenders keep your
                <strong>payment amount the same</strong> and simply
                <strong>shorten the term</strong>. Others may allow you to
                recast or refinance to lower the monthly payment after a large
                prepayment. This calculator assumes your regular payment stays
                constant and the term shrinks.
              </p>

              <h3>
                2. What if my loan has a “precomputed” interest or rule of 78s?
              </h3>
              <p>
                Some older or specialized loans calculate interest upfront. In
                those cases, prepayment may not save as much interest as a
                standard amortizing loan, and the math is different. Always
                check your loan agreement; this calculator is designed for
                typical amortizing loans with interest on the outstanding
                balance.
              </p>

              <h3>
                3. Should I pay off high-interest debt before low-interest debt?
              </h3>
              <p>
                From a purely financial standpoint, it usually makes sense to
                prioritize <strong>higher-rate</strong>
                debt first (credit cards, personal loans) before aggressively
                prepaying low-rate, secured loans like mortgages. However,
                psychological factors and risk tolerance also matter.
              </p>

              <h3>4. How do I know if a prepayment penalty is worth it?</h3>
              <p>Use this calculator to compare:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>Total interest saved from prepayment.</li>
                <li>Minus the prepayment penalty.</li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                If the net savings are positive and you value being debt-free
                sooner, prepayment can still be worthwhile even with a penalty.
              </p>

              <h3>
                5. Can I use this for mortgages, personal loans, and auto loans?
              </h3>
              <p>
                Yes. As long as your loan has a
                <strong>fixed interest rate</strong> and
                <strong>regular amortizing payments</strong>, the calculator
                will give a good approximation. For variable-rate loans or
                complex products, treat the results as an estimate and consult
                your lender for exact figures.
              </p>
